gious, Vatican II, Education, and the State in Atlantic Canada -- tThe Sisters of Our Lady of the Missions in Canada, the Long 1960s, and Vatican II: From Carving Spaces in the Educational State to Living the Radicality of the Gospel -- tPart Four: Changes in Curriculum and the Catholic Classroom after Vatican II -- tThe Conditions of Reception for the Declaration on Christian Education: Secularization and the Educational State of Ontario -- tCatholic Elite Education in Chile: Worlds Apart -- tPart Five: Catholicism and Aboriginal Education in Canada -- tBalancing the Spirit in Aboriginal Catholic Education in Ontario -- tIndigenous Education as Failed Ontological Reconfiguration -- tPart Six: Religious Renewal and Public Pedagogy -- t“The Scandalous Revolutionary Force of the Past”: On Pasolini’s the Gospel According to Saint Matthew -- tConclusion: Catholicism and Education: Points of Intersection, Opposition, and Configuration -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Second Vatican Council (Vatican II), called by Pope John XXIII in 1959, produced sixteen documents that outlined the Church’s attempts to meet increasing calls for modernization in the wake of social and cultural changes that were taking place in the twentieth century. Catholic Education in the Wake of Vatican II is the first work dedicated to the effects of the Second Vatican Council on catholic education in various national and cultural contexts. These original pieces, grounded in archival research, explore the social, political, and economic repercussions of Catholic educational changes in Canada, Europe, and South America. The volume provides insightful analysis of many issues including the tensions between Catholicism and Indigenous education in Canada, the secularization of curriculum in the Catholic classroom, Church-State relations and more. The contributors reveal the tensions between doctrinal faith and socio-economic structures of privilege found within the Church and introduces the reader to complex political interactions within the Church itself in the midst of a rapid era of secularization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aAttridge, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeeman, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruno-Jofre, Rosa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBruno-Jofré, Rosa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Cristián, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDávila, Paulí, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHugonnier, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImbarack, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacdonald, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorcom, Lindsay A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaya, Luis M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinar, William F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSerrano, Gemma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmyth, Elizabeth M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStafford, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValle, Carlos Martínez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZaldivar, Jon Igelmo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZaldívar, Jon Igelmo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat